post_text: Please help. This effort could go a long way in getting high-speed internet access to rural homeowners and businesses.
shared_text:
Kenergy
August 2 at 10:00 AM ·

Kentucky communities deserve to thrive. Rural communities have suffered from a lack of reliable, high-speed internet availability for long enough. Today, we have the opportunity to change that.

The Rural Broadband Acceleration Act will expedite the availability of federal broadband funding and allow those planning to make high-speed broadband service available to thousands of rural communities to quickly start construction.

Share this post and visit https://bit.ly/GORuralBroadbandNOW
to urge Senators Mitch McConnell and Rand Paul to support S.4201 to expedite broadband funding. #RuralBroadbandNOW #BridgetheDigitalDivide @mitchmcconnell @RandPaul

shared_text:
Bradley Schneider
July 28 at 7:27 PM ·

I’ve gotten a question or two about mosquito spraying. The county has been spraying for mosquitos weekday evenings since the first of June, if not sooner than that. The spray truck tries to cover all the county roads and neighborhoods at least twice during the summer. Rain hurts. It both slows down spraying and also creates conditions for mosquito breeding. And we’ve had a lot of rain the last two months. Stay safe!

shared_text:
Bradley Schneider
June 27 at 11:54 AM ·

All of us at Henderson County Government are going to miss this great lady, Nancy Whitledge Watkins. She’s been our solid waste coordinator and recycling director since 2016 and has worked very hard at both assignments. She’s fun-loving, conscientious and multi-talented. She could write a state grant request at 9 a.m. and then be on a fork truck slinging cardboard bales at 10 a.m. She managed her team well and accomplished good things for this county. Sadly for us, Friday was her last day. She was offered a job at the US Postal Service that is a great opportunity for her, and she accepted. I know she’ll knock it out of the park in her new career. Good luck, Nancy!

KYTC District 2
June 15 at 10:24 AM ·

Lane Restriction for Spottsville Bridge on Wednesday
AT&T to relocate fiber optic line

MADISONVILLE, Ky. (June 15, 2020) – AT&T will be moving a fiber optic line Wednesday, June 17, on the Spottsville Bridge in Henderson County. A lane restriction will be in place and traffic will be directed with flaggers between the hours of 8:00 a.m. and 5:00 p.m. The work is scheduled for completion the same day. Motorists are encouraged to reduce their speed and pay attention to flaggers while traveling through this work site.

shared_text:
City of Henderson, KY Government
May 15 at 10:27 AM ·

Team Kentucky Fund Assistance Application Portal is now open. Those who have been significantly financially impacted by the COVID-19 emergency can visit the website, and apply for financial assistance.

The fund is overseen by the Public Protection Cabinet, and is administered through a partnership with Kentucky Community Action Agency. Assistance will be provided in the form of vouchers. The vouchers can be used to pay for rent, electricity, groceries and other qualifying expenses.

Kentucky Community Action Agency will review all applications, to see who qualifies for assistance. To read the criteria to qualify for financial assistance, visit teamkyfund.ky.gov.

FYI: Another way to get financial assistance during the coronavirus outbreak.

City of Henderson, KY Government
May 15 at 10:27 AM ·

Team Kentucky Fund Assistance Application Portal is now open. Those who have been significantly financially impacted by the COVID-19 emergency can visit the website, and apply for financial assistance.

The fund is overseen by the Public Protection Cabinet, and is administered through a partnership with Kentucky Community Action Agency. Assistance will be provided in the form of vouchers. The vouchers can be used to pay for rent, electricity, groceries and other qualifying expenses.

Kentucky Community Action Agency will review all applications, to see who qualifies for assistance. To read the criteria to qualify for financial assistance, visit teamkyfund.ky.gov.

post_text:
A reminder: The period for opting out of having volunteer fire department dues appear on the property tax bills that will be issued this fall will end on May 31. Anyone who owns property in Henderson County outside the city limits of Henderson who does not want to pay the VFD dues with their tax bill should turn in an opt out form by the end of this month. Blank opt out forms can be emailed or sent via regular mail to those requesting one. Call 270-826-3971 to request a form. Or, fill out the form online here: https://www.hendersonky.us/FormCenter/Volunteer-Fire-Departments-8/VOLUNTEER-FIRE-DEPARTMENT-FEES-OPTOUT-PE-54

Those who opt out can still make a direct contribution of any amount to their local volunteer fire department and be considered a member in good standing. Those who don't make a contribution or pay their VFD dues through their tax bills may be subject to a charge of up to $1,000 from VFDs who respond to their properties for emergencies.

A reminder: The period for opting out of having volunteer fire department dues appear on the property tax bills that will be issued this fall will end on May 31. Anyone who owns property in Henderson County outside the city limits of Henderson who does not want to pay the VFD dues with their tax bill should turn in an opt out form by the end of this month. Blank opt out forms can be emailed or sent via regular mail to those requesting one. Call 270-826-3971 to request a form. Or, fill out the form online here: https://www.hendersonky.us/FormCenter/Volunteer-Fire-Departments-8/VOLUNTEER-FIRE-DEPARTMENT-FEES-OPTOUT-PE-54

Those who opt out can still make a direct contribution of any amount to their local volunteer fire department and be considered a member in good standing. Those who don't make a contribution or pay their VFD dues through their tax bills may be subject to a charge of up to $1,000 from VFDs who respond to their properties for emergencies.

This statement was issued Monday by Ron Chapman, who oversees Tyson Foods’ plant in Robards:

“The Tyson Foods Robards, Kentucky facility will cancel production Thursday through Sunday for additional cleaning and sanitation efforts. As a food production company, we follow Good Manufacturing Practices including those relating to sanitation and disinfection of our facilities. While we’ve intensified cleaning and sanitation already, we’re committed to do all we can to keep team members safe including suspending a day of production for additional cleaning.”

From the Henderson County Water District:

April 24, 2020, 3:00 pm

The staff report that Tyson is being very cooperative and implemented extensive on-site employee safety precautions some time ago.

Pete Conrad

post_text:
CORRECTION!!!!

SPOTTSVILLE BRIDGE WILL NOT BE CLOSED

A correction from the Kentucky Transportation Cabinet:

Beginning Friday, April 17, a contractor will be closing KY 2243 from Hillside Lane (MP 2.81) to U.S. 60 (MP 3.02) to construct the waterline relocation as part of the Spottsville Bridge Project. The closure will on be on KY 2243 and will be in place from 7 a.m. to 3:30 p.m.The Spottsville Bridge WILL NOT CLOSE.

KY 2243 will be open Saturday and Sunday (April 18 - 19).

The second closure of KY 2243 will begin on Monday, April 20 at 8 a.m. and remain in place for two weeks while the majority of this work is completed. The closure is scheduled to reopen at 8 a.m. on Monday, May 4. Again, this work pertains only to KY 2243 and not the Spottsville Bridge, which will remain open.

Access will be provided to local properties within the closure limits. There will not be a marked detour.

post_text: Heads-up! Severe weather may be on the way for our region tonight
shared_text:
Henderson Emergency Management
April 8 at 9:05 AM ·

Now is the time to prepare ...

From NWS Paducah:

THIS IS A SERIOUS WEATHER THREAT

An outbreak of severe thunderstorms is forecast as our entire region is under a Level 3 Severe Weather Risk, mainly for this evening, possibly extending until after midnight over western KY. A squall line should develop this evening and per SPC “This squall-line should be accompanied by numerous damaging wind gusts, large hail and a tornado threat.”

Before the squall line development this evening, discrete supercells will be possible later this afternoon and into the evening. Per SPC, “Hailstones of greater than 2 inches in diameter will be possible with the stronger more discrete storms.”

Plan your afternoon and especially your evening around the weather and stay informed via your favorite media outlet and/or via weather.gov/pah.

Ensure your weather radio has fresh batteries and be prepared to shelter!

Of those, there have been 27 confirmed recoveries and two fatalities.

shared_text:
Bradley Schneider
March 29 at 1:17 PM ·

Toured some storm-affected areas in the county this morning with Henderson Emergency Management Director Kenny Garrett. Graham Hill definitely had the highest concentration of damage to homes (see photos). Kenergy crews were there working feverishly to get power back on (as they are wherever there are still outages), but there are dozens of big trees down that took utility lines and poles with them. We saw wind damage all the way from Corydon up to Graham Hill, and I know there was more damage east of that in the Spottsville and Reed areas. From the folks we talked to, it seems insurance reps are out in full force helping their clients. County roads appeared to be clear, but comment on this if you still see blockages. Still no reports of serious injuries, thank goodness. We were impressed and inspired by the neighbors, friends and families who are out there helping each other clear debris and patch up homes. As you all do those wonderful things, please be safe.

post_text: A great man, Carroll Morrow, giving his final out-of-service “10-7” call at the end of his shift on Friday, his last day after 29 years of meritorious duty at the Henderson County Sheriff’s Office. His retirement is well-earned and he leaves an amazing legacy of hard work and integrity. The Sheriff’s Office will miss him, but we’re sure he’s going to thoroughly enjoy spending more time with his family, fishing down at the lakes and not having a set schedule. Every day is Saturday now, Sgt. Morrow. Every day is Saturday.

post_text: Just FYI: A state of emergency was declared for Henderson County today. The declaration is not intended to signal any new threats or more serious developments in the coronavirus outbreak in our community than there were before. It just gives Fiscal Court more flexibility in meeting together to discuss and make decisions on COVID-19 related issues. Under the declaration the court can meet as a quorum and address pressing emergency matters without the normal 24-hour notice to the public, as is usually required by law. Emergency meetings of the Fiscal Court are still open meetings, and media will be notified. Any emergency meetings will also be shown live on Facebook. Again, this emergency declaration does not mean the county thinks our current situation is about to become more dangerous or because we have information about COVID-19 that you do not. This is a technical measure meant simply to give Fiscal Court another option as we continue to work with state and federal authorities to help us all stay safe. Thank you.

From Audubon Area Community Services:

Audubon Area Community Services is still helping clients with utility bills. The office is closed to the public. Someone will be answering phone calls from 8am-3pm. If you receive voicemail leave your name number you will receive a call back.
Items needed:
1) Proof of income for the entire month of February
2) Social Security Cards for everyone in the family
3) Photo ID’s for everyone over the age of 18
4) Disconnect or late notice from utility company

Items can be emailed to cchildress@audubon-Area.com or mgreen@audubon-Area.com

We are also helping with other things during this time. For additional information email Crystal Childress at cchildress@audubon-area.com

post_text:
Update: an individual has tested positive for the coronavirus in Lyon County, the first such outcome west of Louisville.

But, bigger news. By tomorrow, March 18, at 5 pm, Kentucky Gov. Andy Beshear has ordered the following businesses to cease all operations, due to their inability to adhere to social distancing regs by their nature:

Theaters and cinemas
Gyms and exercise facilities
Entertainment venues
Nail salons, hair salons and barbershops
Recreational facilities
Community and recreation centers
Concert venues
Sporting event facilities.

By March 20 the governor has ordered all adult daycare centers to close.

All other businesses can remain open but are strongly encouraged to follow social distancing guidelines.

Kentucky Cabinet for Health and Family Services
February 26 at 9:12 PM ·

At this time we have no confirmed cases and no PUIs (Persons Under Investigation) in Kentucky, but we are actively monitoring every inquiry that comes in. Our Dept. for Public Health is working hard to support state clinicians and local health departments in monitoring for potential cases of this disease. We help monitor those who could be at risk, such as Kentuckians who have recently traveled to China or other countries where COVID-19 is spreading. Our mission is to minimize risk to communities if a patient is at risk or has developed symptoms. Learn more about COVID-19: https://bit.ly/3cm1i2S

text: Heads-up! The Kentucky Transportation Cabinet has announced that the Spottsville Bridge will be completely closed to traffic starting at 6 p.m. on March 6 until 5 a.m. on March 9 as their crews make repairs to the bridge's trusses. A detour will be marked and will most likely direct drivers to utilize the Audubon Parkway to eventually get to the eastern end of Henderson County or the western end of Daviess County.

If you live in a low-lying area that is prone to flood, please make the necessary preparations, including plans for alternate living arrangements if your home becomes dangerous to occupy. More information will be available soon.

Angela Buckman Comer organized the Henderson County Courthouse’s Ugly Christmas Sweater contest this year, and had me act as judge (imagine that). Bradley Schneider is with Bryan Coghill and David Crafton.
November 26, 2019 at 5:10 PM ·

Teamwork! From left, Corydon Civil Defense Fire & Rescue Chief Bryan Coghill (with his son, Mason), Smith Mills VFD Chief Mike Coghill and (far right) Henderson City-County Rescue Squad member Kenny Perkins present Henderson County Sheriff’s Office Col. David Crafton with three AEDs the organizations purchased through the Deaconess Foundation’s Heart Saver initiative. These AEDs could save lives if a deputy is the first one on the scene of a citizen having cardiac issues. Thanks to generous donors, Deaconess and the hard work of Doros Hadjisavva, a Hendersonian and owner of Acropolis Restaurant & Catering, the HCSO now has enough AEDs to outfit every marked car that patrols the county. But we could use more! Message me for info.

October 18, 2019 at 1:24 PM ·

FYI: I have officially rescinded Henderson County's burn ban, effective this afternoon at 5 p.m. Conditions have improved enough to end the ban, but everyone is urged to be very cautious with fires, especially when burning yard waste or debris. Those fires should not be left unattended. The whole region is still under the Kentucky Forestry Division's annual regulation that prohibits debris or field waste fires within 150 feet of forest or brushland between the hours of 6 a.m. and 6 p.m. That ban lasts until Dec. 15. Douglas White WSON Radio Eyewitness News WEHT WTVW 14 NEWS CBS44 WEVV SurfKy News Henderson

shared_text:
Bradley Schneider is with David Crafton.
October 3, 2019 at 11:07 AM ·

Thanks to the fundraising efforts of Doros Hadjisavva and his wife, Ellada, as well as the generosity of the Heart Savers group at the Deaconess Foundation, we delivered to the Henderson County Sheriff’s Dept. five more automated external defibrillators (AEDs) that deputies will keep in their patrol cars. The AEDs could save the lives of those who suffer a cardiac arrest and a deputy is the first one to arrive on-scene. Ed Brady and David Crafton now have seven AEDs for their team, with a goal of getting five more. Contact Penny Robertson Goshert at the Deaconess Foundation to learn more about how you can help.

Bradley Schneider
September 30, 2019 at 6:53 AM ·

FYI. Please share:

In accordance with KRS 149.401 I, Brad Schneider, Judge Executive of Henderson County, hereby impose a Burn Ban for Henderson County, KY. This includes the Cities of Henderson, Robards and Corydon.

Exemptions:

Personal food preparation using outdoor gas or charcoal grills or other self-contained cooking platforms.

Food preparation for community events such as Burgoo or BBQ at which a city or volunteer fire department provides on-site fire protection.

All other open burning is prohibited.

This order is effective immediately and will last until further notice.

Additional open burning information can be found on our Emergency Management website at hendersonema.org.

Thanks for your help in letting the public know about this development.
